{
  "texts": [
    "Never driven by external rewards such as grades, children develop, learn, achieve understanding, self-determination, and autonomy because of their own enacted exploration and embodied intervention onto the world (Montessori, 1996a; 2023; Lillard, 2017; 2019; Batubara et al., 2020; Kvintova et al., 2022; see also: Mohammadi et al., 2023).",
    "If obstructed in their movement and in their choices of activities, children fail to fully develop intellect and personality, \"incapable of controlling the way they interact with their circumstances\" (Moretti, 2021. Pp. 39).",
    "Chosen activities are meaningful, and the child focuses its attention and performs them with an autonomously established increasing precision (Lillard et al., 2021): \"whether moving blocks or…composing poetry, agents engage in activities with internal normative standards that allow them to do the activities well\" (Frierson, 2022, Pp. 49; [emphasis in the original]).",
    "Precision is obtained overcoming mistakes: children need to cultivate \"a friendly feeling toward errors\" and not be scared \"to knock into things\" (Montessori, in: Frierson, 2022, Pp. 50).",
    "\"A 'control of error' that allows students to recognize manageable goals and correct errors\" (Frierson, 2022. Pp. 50) is then implemented in the materials and in the space."
  ]
}